import csv as cs
# City of Leeds Cycle Flow Data: Why it is messy and how to tidy it
*Space-Time Analytics â€” Lab 1*

The city of Leeds is located in the district of West Yorkshire, England. With a population density of approximately 3600 persons per square mile, the city boasts ample transportation options for its residents. These options include railways, busses, trollies, and a network of cycling lanes for bicycle commuters that flow adjacent to the lanes utilized by motor vehicles. 

The city's transport department uses cameras to monitor traffic flow. Since 2010, they have recorded data on the number of cyclists traveling through ten specific intersections.
## Map of Leeds traffic cameras in use for collecting cycle flow data
display(Image("LeedsMap.png", width=900, embed=True))

The data is accessible through datahub.io https://datahub.io/dataset/leeds-annual-cycle-growth.will, and will be particuarly useful to anyone hoping to model bicycle commuter flows. *However*, at first glance, two major problems are immediately apparent:

* The data is stored in separate tables by year, which is not helpful for year-by-year comparison
* The additional commentary for the first two years of data suggests it is unreliable, so only the years 2012, 2013, and 2014 should be used for analytical purposes
### The original "messy" data

Hadley Wickham defines "messy data" in his *'Tidy Data'* article in the Journal of Statistical Software http://vita.had.co.nz/papers/tidy-data.pdf In section 3, Wickham pinpoints the most common offenses:
  • Column headers are values, not variable names.
  • Multiple variables are stored in one column.
  • Variables are stored in both rows and columns.
  • Multiple types of observational units are stored in the same table.
  • A single observational unit is stored in multiple tables.
The Leeds cycle count data is especially guilty of the fifth bullet point, and Wickham's suggested remedy is to combine the tables into a single, tidy table.
The data tables 'twelve', 'thirteen', and 'fourteen' are the data from years 2012, 2013, and 2014 respectively.

twelve = pd.read_csv('2012.csv', sep=',', low_memory=False)
thirteen = pd.read_csv('2013.csv', sep=',', low_memory=False)
fourteen = pd.read_csv('2014.csv', sep=',', low_memory=False)
The original structure for each data table can be seen below.

The structure of each of the original data tables is similar. However, the variable names could be more descript, some of the columns are redundant and unnecessary, and the Sdate column has two variables in each cell. This data could certainly be tidier.
## Tidy Data

Tidy Data, by Hadley Wickham's standards, means:
  • Each variable is in a column.
  • Each observation is in a row.
  • Each observational unit makes up a table.

The original data includes the following elements:
* Sdate: the date and time stamp for the observations made
* Cosit: the camera ID number identifying which of the ten locations the observations were made
* Period: the time (in minutes) in which the observation was made
* LaneNumber: the number of motor vehicle lanes on the road 
* LaneDirection: how many directions the road travels in (1 if one-way, 2 if two-lane with one each way)
* DirectionDescription: the direction the cyclists are traveling 
* Volume: the number of Cyclists observed during the time period
* Flag Text: messages on traffic, data collection issues, and observed holidays
* Unnamed 8: unknown

The columns can be renamed to provide shorter, more descript column headings.

twelve.rename(columns = {'Sdate' : 'Date', 'Cosit' : 'CamID', 'LaneNumber':'Lanes', 'LaneDirection':'Way', 'DirectionDescription':'Dir', 'Volume':'Count'}, inplace=True)
thirteen.rename(columns = {'Sdate' : 'Date', 'Cosit' : 'CamID', 'LaneNumber':'Lanes', 'LaneDirection':'Way', 'DirectionDescription':'Dir', 'Volume':'Count'}, inplace=True)
fourteen.rename(columns = {'Sdate' : 'Date', 'Cosit' : 'CamID', 'LaneNumber':'Lanes', 'LaneDirection':'Way', 'DirectionDescription':'Dir', 'Volume':'Count'}, inplace=True)

Subsetting the tables will eliminate unwanted data columns. Namely these are the Period and FlagText columns.

The Period column can be taken out since the information is redundant. The cyclist counts are taken over a period of 60 minutes for *every* observation made. This is already clear from the information given in the Date column. 

The FlagText column gives a sort of metadata for each observation made. Was there road work on that street? Was the date a holiday? Is the data for that observation invalid? (In this last case, the Count was set to zero.) In any case, this information most likely not needed in the data table and can be referenced from the original data tables later if need be.

twelve = twelve[['Date','CamID','Lanes','Way','Dir','Count']]
thirteen = thirteen[['Date','CamID','Lanes','Way','Dir','Count']]
fourteen = fourteen[['Date','CamID','Lanes','Way','Dir','Count']]
twelve.head(3)
thirteen.head(3)
fourteen.head(3)
The data frames can be combined into one single table now.
leeds = pd.concat([twelve,thirteen,fourteen])
leeds.head(5)
The first column, Date can be made into its own data frame, and split into the date and time.

df = pd.DataFrame(leeds.Date.str.split(' ',1).tolist(),
                                   columns = ['date','time'])
df.head(3)
Then the new data frame can be merged with the rest of the Leeds data into one, **NICE, TIDY, DATA TABLE!!**

Leeds = pd.merge(df, leeds, right_index=True, left_index=True)
Leeds = Leeds[['date','time','CamID','Lanes','Way','Dir','Count']]
Leeds.head(27)

df2 = pd.DataFrame(Leeds["Count"])
plt.figure()
pylab.show((df2.plot.hist(alpha=0.5)))

Just for fun, the aggregate expected value of the counts can be caluclated 
$$
\textrm{E}\{Y(s)\} = \mu(s)
np.mean(df2)
